WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.940
We already talked about mindset previously,
and now you have a general sense of what we

2
00:00:04.940 --> 00:00:06.220
do and who we serve.

3
00:00:06.640 --> 00:00:08.980
This module isn't going to repeat any of
that.

4
00:00:09.160 --> 00:00:13.740
What we're doing here is giving you the
vocabulary to match the conversations you're

5
00:00:13.740 --> 00:00:15.320
already starting to have.

6
00:00:16.500 --> 00:00:19.600
Terminology is different from any other kind
of training.

7
00:00:19.740 --> 00:00:24.020
You're not going to absorb all of this in
one sitting, and that's completely normal.

8
00:00:24.340 --> 00:00:26.000
Expect to come back to this video.

9
00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:29.500
Expect to watch certain sections two or
three times.

10
00:00:30.160 --> 00:00:34.460
The goal right now is familiarity, not
memorization.

11
00:00:35.060 --> 00:00:39.760
The more calls you make, the more these terms
will start clicking into place naturally.

12
00:00:40.160 --> 00:00:41.440
Let's get into it.

13
00:00:42.220 --> 00:00:47.400
A distressed property is a home that's
either in rough physical shape or owned by

14
00:00:47.400 --> 00:00:50.040
someone going through a hard situation in
life.

15
00:00:50.040 --> 00:00:52.140
Maybe the roof is caving in.

16
00:00:52.540 --> 00:00:54.260
Maybe the owner just lost their job.

17
00:00:54.640 --> 00:00:59.520
Maybe someone passed away and left the house
to a family member who lives three states

18
00:00:59.520 --> 00:01:02.220
away and has no idea what to do with it.

19
00:01:03.340 --> 00:01:04.500
Think of it like this.

20
00:01:04.700 --> 00:01:08.750
You know how sometimes you see a car on the
side of the road with the hood up, hazard

21
00:01:08.750 --> 00:01:10.700
lights on, and nobody around?

22
00:01:10.780 --> 00:01:14.380
That car isn't going to sell at full price
on a dealership lot.

23
00:01:14.600 --> 00:01:17.780
Someone is going to come along, fix it up,
and resell it.

24
00:01:17.780 --> 00:01:20.720
That's essentially what happens with
distressed properties.

25
00:01:21.320 --> 00:01:26.000
We come in, we make a fast cash offer, and
we help the seller move on.

26
00:01:27.240 --> 00:01:32.240
Why does this matter? Because every single
person we engage with is a potential

27
00:01:32.240 --> 00:01:33.780
distressed property owner.

28
00:01:34.120 --> 00:01:39.680
The first job in any conversation is to find
out if they're in that situation and to

29
00:01:39.680 --> 00:01:43.300
make sure the right person at BMH takes them
through the next step.

30
00:01:44.120 --> 00:01:49.600
When we say we buy as is, we mean we're not
asking the seller to fix anything.

31
00:01:50.060 --> 00:01:52.760
No repairs, no cleaning, no staging.

32
00:01:53.140 --> 00:01:56.060
We take the house exactly the way it is.

33
00:01:57.160 --> 00:02:02.180
This is a huge relief for sellers who don't
have the money or the energy to fix things

34
00:02:02.180 --> 00:02:05.420
up. On a call, a seller might say something
like,

35
00:02:05.420 --> 00:02:07.320
The place needs a lot of work.

36
00:02:07.740 --> 00:02:10.480
Or, I haven't been able to keep up with
repairs.

37
00:02:11.200 --> 00:02:12.660
That's actually good news.

38
00:02:13.020 --> 00:02:15.300
That's your signal to say, that's totally
fine.

39
00:02:15.540 --> 00:02:17.200
We buy homes in any condition.

40
00:02:18.660 --> 00:02:23.180
An off-market property is a home that is not
listed for sale anywhere publicly.

41
00:02:23.720 --> 00:02:25.400
There's no sign in the yard.

42
00:02:25.620 --> 00:02:27.160
There's no listing online.

43
00:02:27.160 --> 00:02:30.160
The seller hasn't hired a real estate agent.

44
00:02:30.320 --> 00:02:33.020
They may not have even decided they want to
sell yet.

45
00:02:34.260 --> 00:02:36.520
This is the sweet spot for the BMH Group.

46
00:02:37.020 --> 00:02:41.480
We reach out directly to homeowners before they
ever consider going the traditional route.

48
00:02:41.820 --> 00:02:45.870
Think of it like getting a reservation at a
restaurant that hasn't even opened to the

49
00:02:45.870 --> 00:02:49.020
public yet. You're in before anyone else
knows about it.

50
00:02:49.020 --> 00:02:51.700
Now here's an important distinction.

51
00:02:52.540 --> 00:02:57.220
On-market means the property is listed on
something called the MLS.

52
00:02:58.160 --> 00:03:01.260
MLS stands for Multiple Listing Service.

53
00:03:01.920 --> 00:03:06.280
It's a database that licensed real estate
agents use to post homes for sale.

54
00:03:06.640 --> 00:03:12.160
When you see a house listed on Zillow or
Realtor.com, it almost always came from the

55
00:03:12.160 --> 00:03:12.960
MLS.

56
00:03:13.760 --> 00:03:17.080
Here's the thing. We don't target on-market
properties.

57
00:03:17.580 --> 00:03:21.920
By the time a house hits the MLS, there's
usually an agent involved.

58
00:03:22.280 --> 00:03:27.240
The price reflects the market and there's not
much room for us to make the numbers work.

59
00:03:27.500 --> 00:03:32.720
If a seller on a call says, I already have
it listed with an agent or it's on Zillow,

60
00:03:32.720 --> 00:03:34.080
that's an important flag.

61
00:03:34.440 --> 00:03:36.600
Don't hang up, but do note it.

62
00:03:36.900 --> 00:03:41.180
Sometimes listed properties don't sell and
that seller comes back around.

63
00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:46.580
A listed property is simply one currently
for sale through an agent on the MLS.

64
00:03:47.160 --> 00:03:49.880
An expired listing is one that was listed
but never sold.

65
00:03:50.200 --> 00:03:53.160
The seller tried the traditional route and
it didn't work out.

66
00:03:53.360 --> 00:03:59.380
Now they might be frustrated, more motivated,
and very open to a direct cash offer.

67
00:04:00.180 --> 00:04:02.500
Expired listings can be great leads.

68
00:04:03.500 --> 00:04:08.340
Days on market is how long a property has
been sitting on the MLS without selling.

69
00:04:09.020 --> 00:04:14.520
A house listed for 200 days is a house the
seller is probably desperate to get rid of.

70
00:04:15.060 --> 00:04:17.580
High days on market is a motivation signal.

71
00:04:18.980 --> 00:04:23.640
FSBO means the seller is trying to sell the
house themselves without an agent.

72
00:04:24.050 --> 00:04:25.580
They're not paying a commission.

73
00:04:25.580 --> 00:04:28.100
They're handling everything directly.

74
00:04:28.540 --> 00:04:32.940
This often means they're motivated and
willing to talk, which makes them a good

75
00:04:32.940 --> 00:04:34.320
potential lead for us.

76
00:04:35.520 --> 00:04:40.440
Now let's talk about what the BMH Group does
with the properties we put under contract.

77
00:04:41.200 --> 00:04:43.240
Our primary strategy is wholesaling.

78
00:04:43.760 --> 00:04:47.900
Imagine you find a garage sale where someone
is selling a rare collectible for $5

79
00:04:47.900 --> 00:04:49.820
because they don't know what it's worth.

80
00:04:49.820 --> 00:04:53.500
You know a collector who would pay $500 for
it.

81
00:04:53.500 --> 00:04:57.040
So you make a deal with the garage sale
owner to buy it for $5.

82
00:04:57.460 --> 00:05:00.620
Then you go sell it to your collector for
$500.

83
00:05:01.220 --> 00:05:03.000
Your profit is the difference.

84
00:05:03.480 --> 00:05:05.260
That's wholesaling in real estate.

85
00:05:06.280 --> 00:05:11.500
We find a distressed property, get it under
contract at a price that works for the

86
00:05:11.500 --> 00:05:16.920
seller's situation, and then we sell that
contract to an end buyer or cash buyer who

87
00:05:16.920 --> 00:05:19.760
will renovate and resell or rent the
property.

88
00:05:20.100 --> 00:05:23.700
We never have to actually close on the house
ourselves most of the time.

89
00:05:23.740 --> 00:05:25.700
We just facilitate the deal.

90
00:05:26.500 --> 00:05:31.360
When we wholesale, we do it through
something called an assignment of contract.

91
00:05:32.140 --> 00:05:36.520
This is where we transfer our rights in the
purchase agreement to another buyer.

92
00:05:37.060 --> 00:05:41.400
Instead of us closing on the property, the
end buyer closes on it.

93
00:05:41.960 --> 00:05:46.480
Our fee for finding the deal and putting it
together is called the assignment fee.

94
00:05:47.820 --> 00:05:52.400
Sometimes instead of assigning the contract,
we do what's called a double close.

95
00:05:52.980 --> 00:05:57.380
This means we actually purchase the property
and then immediately sell it to the end

96
00:05:57.380 --> 00:05:59.580
buyer in two back-to-back closings.

97
00:05:59.740 --> 00:06:03.900
This is a little more involved, but it
protects our profit margin when needed.

98
00:06:04.920 --> 00:06:11.000
Subject to means we purchase a property
subject to the existing mortgage staying in

99
00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:13.920
place. The seller's loan doesn't get paid
off.

100
00:06:14.240 --> 00:06:18.380
We take ownership, but the original mortgage
stays in the seller's name.

101
00:06:18.820 --> 00:06:21.300
Think of it like taking over someone's car
payments.

102
00:06:22.880 --> 00:06:25.980
Seller financing means the seller acts as
the bank.

103
00:06:26.360 --> 00:06:31.660
Instead of us going to a lender, we make
payments directly to the seller over time.

104
00:06:31.660 --> 00:06:37.380
You likely won't negotiate these on calls,
but knowing they exist lets you confidently

105
00:06:37.380 --> 00:06:42.020
say, our team has several ways to structure
this depending on the situation.

106
00:06:43.440 --> 00:06:46.700
We target distressed, off-market properties.

107
00:06:46.800 --> 00:06:49.400
We buy as-is for cash.

108
00:06:49.900 --> 00:06:55.660
We primarily wholesale, which means we get a
property under contract and sell that

109
00:06:55.660 --> 00:06:58.520
contract to an end buyer for a profit.

110
00:06:58.520 --> 00:07:04.520
The MLS is the public listing database
agents use, and we generally avoid on-market

111
00:07:04.520 --> 00:07:10.400
properties. Expired listings and FSBO
sellers are worth noting as potential leads.

112
00:07:10.760 --> 00:07:16.300
The first job in any conversation is
identifying motivated sellers and getting them

113
00:07:16.300 --> 00:07:17.100
talking.

114
00:07:17.980 --> 00:07:19.700
That's your core vocabulary.

115
00:07:20.360 --> 00:07:21.480
Hang on to these terms.

116
00:07:21.760 --> 00:07:24.340
You'll hear them again and again out in the
field.

117
00:07:24.940 --> 00:07:25.840
Let's keep moving.
